EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The wildfire burned through 1468 acres of timber, brush, and grass five miles northeast of Leavenworth.  The cause of the fire is still under investigation.  No structures were lost in this fire.

A small wildfire quickly grew to 51 acres along Depot Springs Road in south Spokane County due to breezy winds.  The fire burned through tall grass, meadows, and timber patches.  The fire began between Spangle and Cheney around 1200 PST and was contained by 1600 PST.  Five homes were threatened but none were burned.  Two miles of new fencing was burned in the fire.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Tree limbs approx 4-7 inches in diameter down from thunderstorm wind gusts.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of thunderstorms rolled through the basin area on Sunday August 25th. Some of which had: heavy rain, blowing dust, strong gusty winds, and hail. The highest wind speed measured was 71 MPH and the largest hail reported was 0.875 inches.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees and power lines were knocked down from strong thunderstorm winds across east and southeastern sections of Othello.  Reports from the utility company included:  power lines down from a fallen tree two miles southeast of Othello, a downed power pole six miles southeast of Othello, and another power pole downed six miles southeast of Warden.  A newspaper also reported at least eight large trees blown down in the town of Lind.  The downed trees resulted in damage to fences and power lines.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stationary trough of low pressure along the Pacific Northwest Coastline resulted in moist, unstable, southwesterly flow over the Inland Northwest.  A shortwave embedded within the flow, triggered thunderstorms during the afternoon hours of August 25, 2013.  The storms originated in the Lower Columbia Basin and quickly moved through the Basin and into the northern mountain regions of Washington and the Idaho Panhandle.  A strong squall line emerged from this activity which created damaging winds resulting in a dust storm and numerous downed trees and power lines.  There was one fatality and one injury at campground from a large tree falling on a tent.  Several other areas experienced property damage.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Roughly fifty customers in the Mae Valley subdivision of Moses Lake lost power when strong thunderstorm winds damaged five different power poles holding transmission lines.|As the gust front moved into northern sections of Grant County, law enforcement reported numerous trees and power poles downed in and around Grand Coulee.  Overall, 6500 customers loss power across Grant County during the storm.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Spokane NWS clocked a wind gust of 62 mph on the RSOIS.  Numerous trees, some large, were downed in Nine Mile Falls area, especially along West Charles Road.  Some trees were uprooted and other were snapped halfway up the trunk.  Trees fell on a combination of roofs, outbuildings, fences, and power lines resulting in multiple power outages.  A large tree was uprooted along Highway 2 in the Deep Creek community.  A large tree fell on a power line in Chattaroy leading to 178 power outages.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: In the town of Harrington, two large trees were split.  One tree was located on the golf course and second on 5th and Sherlock.  No damage was noted to the property.  Widespread two to four inch branches were scattered on ground around town.  The Odessa Agrimet Sensor clocked a peak wind gust of 57 miles per hour.  Several trees were downed in Davenport but no property damage was reported.  One tree did land on a powerline leading to 29 power outages.  A large tree was blown down at the Sherman Cemetary.  A greenhouse was destroyed on a property located seven miles north of Reardan.  The Spring Canyon RAWS located three miles southeast of Coulee Dam clocked a wind gust of 65 miles per hour.  The storm also knocked down multiple trees at the Lakeview Terrace mobile home park.  Two mobile homes were damaged.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous trees and power lines were downed within and around Coulee City.  Downed trees blocked roads, damaged vehicles, boat trailers, street signs, and homes.  A large tree fell across State Route 155 closing the highway for over three hours.  The roof was partially torn off at the Coulee Dam Casino.  Several signs were also damaged at the casino.  Due to the roof damage, moderate rains trailing behind the wind resulted in water damage to portions of the casino and offices.  The Spring Canyon RAWS located three miles southeast of Coulee Dam clocked a wind gust of 65 miles per hour.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A strong gust front associated with a thunderstorm squall resulted in numerous trees and power lines downed throughout the county.  Over 400 power outages were reported within the communities of Ford, Fruitland, Clayton, and Colville.  The Midnite Mine RAWS located six miles northwest of Wellpinit clocked a wind gust of 57 mph.  A DOT sensor located one mile west of Suncrest clocked a wind gust of 55 mph.  Both sensors experience some degree of sheltering.  One tree did fall on a house but the exact location is unknown.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous houses across sections of Omak east of Highway 97 between Omak River Road and Vista Vu Drive had shingles torn off the roof and large trees blown down.  One house near the intersection of Kruse Street and West Parkway Street had eight panels of cedar fencing blown down.  A few of the posts which were held down by concrete were snapped in half.  In addition to the wind, damage to the fence was likely due to the neighbors small metal shed which was tossed roughly 150 yards.  Metal roofing from a building at the Omak shooting range was peeled off.  Numerous other trees were blown down in Eastside Park and surrounding area.  Downed trees and damage to structures was also reported in the adjacent Colville Indian Reservation, specifically along Columbia River Road, Cold Springs Road, and North End Omak Lake Road including the Paschal Sherman Indian School.  The public relayed that Boy Scout Camp Bonaparte on Bonaparte Lake north of Wauconda also received significant damage to three buildings and the storm knocked down a swath of trees.  The Kramer RAWS clocked a wind gust to 62 mph before the storm entered city limits of Omak.  A Davis weather station located on private property in Okanogan measured a wind gust to 66 mph.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A negatively tilted shortwave trough lifted through Central Washington during the early afternoon hours of August 29th.  The air mass over the region was rather unstable and moist leading to the development of an isolated rotating supercell.  The storm produced damaging winds in excess of 60 mph as it tracked northward through the Okanogan Valley.  A majority of the damage occurred across eastern sections of Omak, Washington and the adjacent Colville Indian Reservation.  A NWS storm survey indicated the damage was from straight line winds but several reports from the public and images suggested a gustnado may have developed along the leading gust front.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail was mostly half an inch in diameter, but there were some hail stones up to 1.5 inches in diameter.  Time of the event was estimated by radar.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Post frontal thunderstorms developed across the Northeast Blue Mountains during the late afternoon hours.  Just enough sunshine in the afternoon destabilized the atmosphere to create surface based convective available potential energy of 500 to 1,000 J/KG.  This was just enough energy in a marginally sheared environment for a supercell thunderstorm that produced severe hail.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A 6 inch limb broke off and damaged a fence four miles south of La Crosse, and the power line to a residence was pulled out by the strong winds.  Tree limbs up to six inches in diameter were broken off five miles south-southeast of Winona.  Finally, at least ten trees were blown over in the town of Endicott.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deep closed low pressure system over southwest Oregon ejected a negatively tilted shortwave trough of lower pressure across southeast Washington.  Surface based instability of 500 to 1,000 J/KG and 0 to 6 km shear of 40 knots during the afternoon was enough to spawn a severe thunderstorm that tracked north across the Washington Palouse.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A flash flood down the Colockum Creek drainage washed out Tarpiscan Road at the Colockum Creek bridge.  Colockum Road, Kingsbury Road, and Agnew Road were closed due to the damage.  Multiple homes were damaged along the Colockum Creek Drainage as well by rocks, trees and other debris that traveled with the flood wave.  Damage costs were estimated.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level low pressure system over western Oregon ejected a negatively tilted shortwave trough of lower pressure over the region during the evening hours of September 5th.  Precipitable water values were twice the normal value for early September.  A line of strong thunderstorms tracked across east-central Washington bringing strong winds and heavy rain.  The hardest hit areas were across the Waterville Plateau, the Wenatchee area and east slopes of the northern Cascades.  Strong winds did result in some fallen trees, but the greatest impact was due to the heavy rainfall.  Training thunderstorms and intense rainfall resulted in flash flooding across multiple drainages.  Recent burn scars from 2012 and 2013 wildfires also helped to create a damaging flash flood event.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flash flooding from Number 2 Canyon blocked a portion of Number 2 Canyon Road above milepost 3.  Flood waters reached as far as western Wenatchee.  Flood waters also damaged homes and property to private residences in the Canyon.  Damage costs were estimated.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An organized cluster of severe thunderstorms moved across the interior pacific northwest. These thunderstorms were very strong wind producers, with blowing dust ahead of the main gust front. Areas would have visibilities reduced below one quarter of a mile for a brief period of time. The strongest estimated wind gust was 77 mph.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Visibility was reduced to 50 feet in Warden.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A negatively tilted shortwave trough of lower pressure interacted with some surface based instability of near 1,000 J/KG in northern Oregon to spawn a squall line that traversed northward across eastern Washington.  Strong winds mixed down to the surface along the squall line to created widespread damaging wind gusts.  The squall line could be classified as a Haboob as the strongest winds occurred out ahead of the thunderstorms that kicked up a massive dust cloud.  The Haboob hit the Moses Lake area and Upper Columbia Basin the hardest with widespread wind damage reported.  The dust cloud resulted in a rapid reduction in visibility to near zero in places.  Impacts from the Haboob were felt as far north as Coulee City eastward into Spokane and into Deer Park.  Strong damaging winds and reduced visibility due to dust were reported across these areas as well.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: EF1 tornado on the ground for 5 minutes or less. Path  length about 1 mile. Width 75 yards. Max wind speed estimated at 110 mph. EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong winds uprooted trees that fell into the Pend Oreille PUD���s 115 kV transmission line near Box Canyon Dam. The outage affected approximately 3,000 customers between Dalkena and Ione.  Other smaller outages occurred throughout the county and kept line crews busy through the night.  A trained spotter reported an uprooted tree five miles west of Newport.  The size of the tree was unknown.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong north jet along the British Columbia Coastline drove a cold low pressure system southward from Western Canada into the Inland Northwest on October 27th.  As low pressure deepened over Oregon and an arctic high pressure cell slide down the Continental Divide, strong northeast pressure gradients and cold advection set up across  Eastern Washington and Northern Idaho resulting in strong, damaging winds.  Locations across the Columbia Basin, Northeast Mountains, and Palouse experienced several downed trees and numerous power outages.  At the height of the storm, over eleven thousand customers experienced power outages across Northeastern Washington and Northern Idaho.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained spotter 6 miles northeast of Bellingham measured a wind gust of 65 mph and reported the power was out.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Moderate northeast outflow wind in western Whatcom county brought a brief gale to the northern inland waters and also caused brief high wind near Bellingham.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Multiple trees were blown down blocking highway 206 near mile post 12.  Highway 206 was closed for over 24 hours until crews were able to remove the debris.  At 19th and Arthur on the South Hill, the top of a 50 year Ponderosa Pine was snapped off blocking the street and taking a tangle of cable and phone lines with it.  Numerous power outages were observed across the Spokane Area.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong north jet along the British Columbia Coastline drove a cold low pressure system southward from Western Canada into the Inland Northwest on October 27th. At the height of the storm, over eleven thousand customers experienced power outages across Northeastern Washington and Northern Idaho.

A strong low pressure system tracked across southern British Columbia, Canada.  A strong low level jet in the warm sector of the system brought heavy snowfall to the mountains of northeast Washington.  Windy conditions ensued across the Spokane area and in the mountain valleys north of Spokane as an occluded front pushed through in the afternoon and evening.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: At Cortright Creek Trailhead, Packwood, a hunter was in his tent when the top of an old growth snapped due to the high winds and fell onto the  tent from approximately 100 feet high. The tree top struck the  tent, hitting the hunter directly in the head causing fatal injury.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deep low moved NE across northwest Washington.  Strong southerly wind developed over the interior, with strong onshore flow on the coast.  High wind reports were scattered, but a few hundred thousand people lost power in the Seattle area.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Multiple power outages across the Spokane area due to wind and downed trees on power lines.  Damage costs were estimated.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure system tracked across southern British Columbia, Canada.  A strong low level jet in the warm sector of the system brought heavy snowfall to the mountains of northeast Washington.  Windy conditions ensued across the Spokane area and in the mountain valleys north of Spokane as an occluded front pushed through in the afternoon and evening.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Tree on power lines knocked out power to 23 customers.  Damage costs were estimated.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure system tracked across southern British Columbia, Canada.  A strong low level jet in the warm sector of the system brought heavy snowfall to the mountains of northeast Washington.  Windy conditions ensued across the Spokane area and in the mountain valleys north of Spokane as an occluded front pushed through in the afternoon and evening.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy wet snow fell across the Spokane area during the morning commute.  This resulted in slick driving conditions across the area with 80 vehicle collisions reported.  Numerous vehicles spun out descending out of the Spokane South Hill area; some of these roads were closed off due to the volume of accidents.  Multiple collisions reported on Highway 395 at milepost 175, four miles south of Deer Park; both lanes were blocked with long delays for motorists traveling that route.  Numerous vehicles were stuck traveling southbound on 395 on the Wandermere Hill. No serious injuries were reported.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A slow moving warm front produced snow across the Spokane and Nine Mile Falls areas during the morning hours.  The front stalled over the area with snow accumulations up to around two to three inches reported.  Snow consistency was wet and slushy and resulted in poor traction on area roadways.  Heaviest snowfall occurred during the morning commute when road traffic was at its peak.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wet snow during the morning commute resulted in slick driving conditions along Highway 291 near Suncrest.  The Big Sandy hill in this area was closed for several hours due to vehicle spin outs.

A strong low pressure system dropped out British Columbia, Canada into northeast Washington.  This created a boundary of cold continental air to the north and maritime polar air from the south.  Valley locations saw a mixture of rain and snow in northeast Washington.  Some mountain valley locations did pick heavy snowfall accumulations, but amounts over the area varied.  Heaviest snowfall accumulations occurred in the mountains.
A strong push of moisture and progressively lowering snow levels led to several inches of snow accumulation over the Blue Mountains. Storm total snow was 11 inches at the Touchet Snotel.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Westport had sustained wind of 40 mph off and on for a few hours.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong onshore flow brought brief high wind to the central coast and the Admiralty Inlet area.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The KNUW ASOS reported sustained wind of 40 mph with a gust of 63 mph.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong onshore flow brought brief high wind to the central coast and the Admiralty Inlet area.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Sustained winds of 45 mph were measured at US 101 Megler Bridge(ODT76) with a gust of 58 mph. Cape Disappointment (82SW1) had a wind gust of 53 mph with a maximum sustained wind of 44 mph.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure center, approximately 1000 millibars moved over Southwest Washington near Gray's Harbor, Washington and produced Strong winds for the Southwest Washington Coast.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Freezing fog resulted in icy conditions on an overpass along Interstate 90 in Medical Lake.  A pickup truck heading eastbound was driving too fast for the conditions and lost control.  The pickup truck proceeded to swerve into the opposite lane triggering a multiple vehicle collision.  One of the vehicles involved in the collision was a semi-truck that collided into two other vehicles; one of the vehicles struck by the semi-truck resulted in a fatality; eight other injuries were also reported with the accident.  The eastbound lanes of Interstate 90 were blocked just west of the Four Lakes exit for hours.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong high pressure in place with a moist boundary layer produced prime conditions for radiation fog.  Temperatures dipped into the mid-twenties overnight into the early morning hours with dense fog reported.  The combination of thick fog and freezing temperatures likely resulted in some riming on area roadways.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Freezing fog resulted in some icy conditions on Interstate 90 between Evergreen and Barker Road at around 0800PST.  The first accident was a pickup truck that had rolled over upside down.  The driver of the vehicle had to be cut out.  Four other vehicles slid on the same patch of ice during the morning hours.  None of the accidents resulted in serious injuries.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Eastern Washington was under a transitioning weather pattern as high pressure was being broken down by an overrunning warm front.  Freezing fog formed under the presence of the high pressure ridge during the early morning hours.  This produced slick road surfaces for the morning commute.  The warm front moved through in the afternoon with a mixture of precipitation reported from light snow, freezing rain and sleet.  Although this weather system was weak, enough freezing precipitation was produced to result in a thin layer of ice on surfaces across the Spokane area into the overnight hours.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A mixture of snow, freezing rain and sleet during the afternoon hours resulted in slick road conditions across the area.  Numerous vehicle collisions were reported: a two-car collision near Hatch Street, a two-car collision just north of Hawthorne Road, a one-car collision three miles south of Deer Park, and along Interstate 90 between mileposts 275 and 277.  Multiple slide-offs and two rollover collisions were also reported on Highway 195 between Hatch Street and Mullen Hill Road.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Eastern Washington was under a transitioning weather pattern as high pressure was being broken down by an overrunning warm front.  Freezing fog formed under the presence of the high pressure ridge during the early morning hours.  This produced slick road surfaces for the morning commute.  The warm front moved through in the afternoon with a mixture of precipitation reported from light snow, freezing rain and sleet.  Although this weather system was weak, enough freezing precipitation was produced to result in a thin layer of ice on surfaces across the Spokane area into the overnight hours.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Valley locations below 3000 feet across northern Stevens and Pend Oreille Counties received between three and five inches of snow.  Six to fourteen inches of snow fell above 3000 feet.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong winter storm impacted the Inland Northwest in two phases.  During the first phase, a deep trough of low pressure dropped southward from British Columbia into the region.  Ahead of the trough, a warm moist conveyor belt of subtropical moisture delivered a shield of isentropically driven precipitation.  Snow levels were driven upward rising above 3000 feet during the first phase of the storm.  The second phase of the storm occurred on December 2nd as the trough sagged into Eastern Washington.  Snow levels fell to valley floors and numerous convective snow showers developed and pivoted around a nearly stationary 700 millibar low.  A majority of the lowland snow came with the second phase of the storm.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: An 88 year old woman wandered from her nursing home, became disoriented, and died outdoors. The Cowlitz County Coronor ruled the cause of death Hypothermia. The media reported temperatures of 28 degrees early Friday. Mesonet stations in Longview reported a minimum temperaure of 25 degrees at station AP806 and 27 degrees at LOPW1.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Cold High Pressure east of the Cascades combined with offshore winds and clear nights resulted in abnormally cold temperatures for Southwest Washington.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Sandy Point Shores recorded sustained 40 mph wind a couple of times in the morning.  It also recorded gusts of 58 mph or higher off and on over a longer period, from early in the morning until late in the evening.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Northeast outflow wind from the Fraser River in British Columbia brought isolated high wind to the western Whatcom county area.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The temperature and wind from the Bonneville Power Administration's weather station at Augspurger Mountain calculate to wind chills of -15 to -25 degrees Fahrenheit.  Temperatures were as low as 3 degrees with east winds 20 mph with gusts to 40 mph.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Cold air from a strong High East of the Cascades combined with strong east winds resulted in extremely cold wind chills for the Washington Cascades.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind chills values of -15 to -20 degrees Fahrenheit were observed.  Some mountain locations above 5000 feet observed wind chills as cold as -30 degrees Fahrenheit.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An arctic air mass spilled into the Inland Northwest between the 6th and 7th of December.  The combination of single digit temperatures and winds on the order of 10 to 25 mph with gusts in excess of 40 mph created wind chills between minus eighteen and minus twenty degrees Fahrenheit in the valleys and up to minus fifty degrees Fahrenheit in the mountains.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Widespread wind chills of -8 to -16 degrees Fahrenheit were observed across the Okanogan Valley but scattered observation platforms measured wind chills between -18 to -26 degrees Fahrenheit.  The coldest wind chill of -26 degrees Fahrenheit was observed nine miles west southwest of Wauconda.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind chills dipped between -15 and -20 degrees Fahrenheit at locations, especially those  exposed to north and northeast winds.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Light slush and excessive speed along Highway 195 led to a three vehicle accident twenty miles north of Colfax.  Five people were injured but there were no fatalities.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Light snow started to fall over the Washington Palouse during the late evening hours of December 12th.  Light slushy accumulations along Highway 195 created slick driving conditions.  The combination of icy roads and excessive speeds led to a three vehicle accident and five injuries.  Observation platforms near the accident only measured between a trace and one hundredth by the time of the collision and it is unclear if roads were already icy from antecedent moisture re-freezing.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A motorists traveling along State Route 211 was thought to be using excessive speed for the icy conditions when his car slid off the road, hit a ditch, and went airborne. The car eventually came to rest on its tires but the driver was killed in the accident.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A combination of freezing fog and moisture from recent rains re-freezing to roadways created icy conditions during the evening of December 14th.  A motorists traveling along State Route 211 lost control of his car, slid off the road, hit a ditch, and flipped the vehicle.  The car eventually came to rest on its tires but the driver was killed in the accident.  Law enforcement determined that the driver was going too fast for the conditions.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moderate to heavy snow fell between 1400 and 1600 PST leading to multiple accidents during the evening commute across the Spokane Area.  Snowfall amounts were generally between two and four inches.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A trough of low pressure had become established over the Inland Northwest by the 19th of December as a ridge of high pressure anchored over the Eastern Pacific.  Meanwhile, a fetch of subtropical moisture topping the offshore ridge became aimed into the region by late on the 19th and majority of the 20th.  Strong isentropic processes ahead of a stalled warm front led to a period of moderate to heavy snow across portions of Eastern Washington and Northern Idaho.  Most locations east of a line from Republic to Ritzville picked up between two and four inches.  Slightly heavier amounts were observed across the Palouse.  Slick conditions led to numerous car accidents across the region with the worst accident occurring at mile post 229 along Interstate 90.  Ten cars were involved resulting in several injuries and one fatality.  The Washington State Patrol reported to over ninety collisions that afternoon across Spokane, Adams, Whitman, and Stevens Counties.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts across the Washington Palouse ranged between four and seven inches.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moderate snow, slick conditions, and excessive speed was responsible for a ten car pile up along Interstate 90 seven miles east of Ritzville at 1246 PST.  Eleven people were involved in the crash, four which were injured and one which died on the scene.  Eight of the ten cars were totaled.  Snowfall totals at the time of the accident were generally around an inch.  Roughly an hour later, a car rolled over at mile post 77 along Highway 395, eighteen miles south of Ritzville.  The driver of the vehicle suffered serious injuries.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong wind knocked out power to nearly 90,000 customers in western Washington.  A landslide blocked a road near Index, cutting off access to about 90 homeowners.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snowfall above 3,000 feet in elevation with over a foot reported in the mountains, mainly near the Cascade crest.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deep fetch of Pacific moisture brought heavy snow to the mountains and moderate to heavy rain to the valleys across the area overnight on January 10th into the 11th.  Localized flooding was observed in the northeast mountains of Washington due to a combination of rainfall, snow melt and frozen soils.  Rainfall amounts were generally up into the half inch to one inch range for this period, which typically would not cause flooding if not in combination with low elevation snow melt and frozen soils preventing water from seeping into the ground.  Flooding impacts were minor and limited to low spots in the terrain, in urban areas and along small streams.  Rain and heavy snow was followed by a strong cold front passage during the early morning hours of January 11th with strong and damaging winds observed across the much of the area.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous reports of sustained wind or gusts in the high wind category were reported, from the KNUW ASOS, from a mesonet location in Port Townsend, and from the Keystone ferry dock.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Prefrontal southeast high winds occurred on the coast and over the north interior. This was the first of three separate high wind episodes.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong Pacific Storm brought windy conditions to the Southwest Washington coast and the Willapa Hills.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deep fetch of Pacific moisture brought heavy snow to the mountains and moderate to heavy rain to the valleys across the area overnight on January 10th into the 11th.  Localized flooding was observed in the northeast mountains of Washington due to a combination of rainfall, snow melt and frozen soils.  Rainfall amounts were generally up into the half inch to one inch range for this period, which typically would not cause flooding if not in combination with low elevation snow melt and frozen soils preventing water from seeping into the ground.  Flooding impacts were minor and limited to low spots in the terrain, in urban areas and along small streams.  Rain and heavy snow was followed by a strong cold front passage during the early morning hours of January 11th with strong and damaging winds observed across the much of the area.

Strong winds moved into the interior Pacific Northwest over the January 10-12th weekend. Several reports of high wind gusts and damage were recorded with these winds. Wind gusts in MPH were reported: (76) Hanford, (71) southwest of Harrah, (70) Hanford, (68) north of West Richland,  (66) Hanford, (65) south west of Harrah, (64) southeast Hanford, (64) Hanford, (62) northwest of West Richland, (62) north east of Sunnyside, (61) southwest of Harrah, (61) east of Glenwood, (61) east of Selah, (61) north of Richland, (60) west northwest of Bickleton, (60) west of Basin City, (60) north northeast of Sunnyside, (59) southeast of Eltopia, (59) south of Yakima, (58) northeast of Sunnyside, (58) east of Goldendale, (58) southeast of Dayton, (58) Hanford, (58) west of Basin City, and sustained winds of 45 mph just west of College Place.  Also strong winds downed a tree into power lines causing a power outage in Trout Lake.  Trees also fell across Highway 141.  A semi Truck was blown over on Highway 240 and the driver was hospitalized.  Trees were reported down in Dayton.  A trained spotter reported small trees down an a 4.5 foot childs playhouse was carried from their backyard to their front yard.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A ten inch diameter tree snapped off in the Five Mile Prairie area north of Spokane; some houses also lost shingles in the area.  There was also a report of an old growth tree that lost four large branches with a girth of eight inches in diameter north of Davenport.  One of these branches flew about ten feet away from the tree.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Local reporter passed along information about numerous trees and power poles down in the Roslyn area and Cle Elum area.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: January 13th High Wind Event for the East Slopes of the Washington Cascades.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Bonneville Power Administration reported issues of riming on their transmission lines running from the Mead area (Bell substation) out onto the west plains.  Avista Utility also reported riming on their transmission lines with power outages reported across the Spokane area.  This included a broken conductor and broken poles between the Four Mounds area to the Idaho state border.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: This period was dominated by a strong upper level ridge of high pressure.  Subsidence associated with this ridge trapped low level moisture with widespread fog developing across the area.  Freezing temperatures and dense fog produced some rime on power lines leading to power outages across the area.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong East winds tipped a semi-trailer over while traveling across the Glen Jackson Bridge on January 23rd. This accident resulted in traffic delays on Interstate 205 and closed boat traffic for just over an hour. Additional winds on January 24th resulted in the collapse of a carport at a Vancouver apartment complex. Over 2000 Clark Power Utility customers lost power for around an hour due to downed tree limbs on power lines.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level ridge resulted in gusty easty winds through the Columbia River Gorge and Vancouver Area. These winds resulted in minor damage including tipping over a semi-trailer on the Glen Jackson Bridge.

CZ_NAME_STR: WEST SLOPES CENTRAL CASCADES AND PASSES (ZONE)
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Washington DOT at Snoqualmie Pass and White Pass reported ice accumulation of 0.25 inch from freezing rain.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong, cold easterly flow ahead an approaching warm front produced a mix of snow and freezing rain in the Cascades passes, with ice accumulations of 0.25 inch or more at both Snoqualmie Pass and White Pass.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Widespread storm total snowfall amounts of two to five inches reported.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deepening shortwave trough of low pressure spun up a low pressure system at the surface.  This low pressure system swung through a strong warm front that tapped into an atmospheric river with sub-tropic origins out of the Pacific Ocean.  There were two regions in eastern Washington that experienced heavy snowfall with most other areas seeing rain or light snowfall before transitioning over to rain.  The first area to receive heavy snowfall was in the lee of the northern Cascade Mountains.  Thermal profiles during the event for this area supported snow due to cold air damning.  Strong warm air advection across the basin resulted in mostly rain with heavy snow observed further north where temperatures were colder across the Spokane area and northeast mountains of Washington.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind chill values varied due to complex terrain and sheltering. Windier locations experienced wind chills between minus 15 and minus 20 degrees Fahrenheit. Wind chills in the sheltered valleys only dropped between minus 5 and minus 12 degrees Fahrenheit.  The Deer Park ASOS observed a wind chill of minus 20 degrees Fahrenheit.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An Arctic air mass spilled into the Inland Northwest between the 4th and 5th of February. The combination of single digit temperatures and winds on the order of 10 to 25 mph with gusts in excess of 30 mph created wind chills between minus fifteen and minus twenty-five degrees Fahrenheit in the valleys and up to minus thirty degrees Fahrenheit in the mountains during the morning hours on the 5th.   Bitterly cold wind chills continued during the morning of the 6th but were paired with slightly cooler temperatures and weaker winds.  The cold and bitterly cold wind chills led to school closures in the Ephrata School District.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind chill values of minus 15 to minus 20 degrees Fahrenheit were observed across the West Plains and higher benches surrounding the city of Spokane.  More sheltered locations only observed winds chills between minus 10 and minus 15 degrees Fahrenheit.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Temperatures in the single digits combined with persistent 20 to 30 mph winds produced wind chills in the -15 to -20 degrees Fahrenheit range.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An Arctic air mass combined with strong easterly winds resulted in extremely low wind chill values for the Cascades.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Very cold temperatures and winds near 10 mph resulted in wind chills of minus 10 to minus 21 across the zone.  The coldest reading of minus 21 was at the Teepee Seed Orchard RAWS.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A band of Heavy snow moved through Clark County, with heavier snow early in the day than the rest of the Greater Portland/Vancouver metro area. Snow accumulations were generally 5 to 9 inches. A blogger reported 9.5 inches of snow in Ridgefield, and we received a Facebook post of 7.5 inches of snow in Salmon Creek. A HAM amateur radio operator repoted 7 inches of snow in Battle Ground.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A preceding cold arctic air mass combined with a moist Pacific storm resulted in widespread heavy snow for Southwest Washington. East winds through the Columbia River Gorge maintained colder air to the north where the precipitation fell mainly as snow.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Biddle Butte gusted greater than 35 mph with a peak gust of 60 mph, and a CWOP station in Washougal (AP164) frequently gusted to 25 mph with a peak of 44 mph. There were no snow reports with in this snow, but snow reports near by support that 4 to 8 inches of snow in the area. Near by Cascade Locks reported 8 inches of snow.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Preceding cold arctic air mass combined with Strong East winds and a moist front resulted in blizzard conditions for the Western Columbia River Gorge.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Although there were no reports on the Washington side of the Central Columbia River Gorge there were several reports of heavy snow in the more populated areas just across the River in Oregon. The Hood River County Emegency Manager reported 10 inches of snow in hood River. The oregon Department of Transportation reported 9 inches of snow in Hood River, and 8 inches in Cascade Locks. With these observations it is estimated that 7 to 12 inches of snow fell on the Washington side of the Central Columbia River Gorge.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A preceding cold arctic air mass combined with a moist Pacific storm resulted in widespread heavy snow for Southwest Washington. East winds through the Columbia River Gorge maintained colder air to the north where the precipitation fell mainly as snow.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Light snow began early in the morning, then increased during the afternoon resulting in a Winter Weather Advisory being upgraded to a Winter Weather Warning. A person from the gernal public reported 7 inches of snow in Woodland, and two trained NWS spotters reported 6 inches of snow at Kalama and Longview.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A preceding cold arctic air mass combined with a moist Pacific storm resulted in widespread heavy snow for Southwest Washington. East winds through the Columbia River Gorge maintained colder air to the north where the precipitation fell mainly as snow.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts ranged from three to four inches with locally up to five inches.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong Pacific jet with ties to subtropical moisture setup across central Oregon allowing an active storm track along the Washington, Oregon border.  The second low pressure system in as many days took aim on southeastern Washington during the overnight and morning hours of the 8th of February.  A band of light to moderate snow on the northeastern periphery brought one to three inches of snow across the Washington Palouse.  A third low pressure system during the evening of the 8th into the morning of the 9th dropped another three to four inches.  Meanwhile, northeast winds drawn into the system continued to bring modified arctic air from Canada into the region.  The combination of temperatures in the teens and northeast winds between 15 and 25 mph resulted in blowing snow and large drifts across the Palouse closing sections of Highway 27 on each the 8th and 9th of February.  Road closures on the 8th were centered between mile posts 59 and the community of Latah.  On the 9th, Highway 27 was closed between mile posts 48 and 63.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two to three inches of snow fell across southern portions of zone 35, mainly in Adams County.  Northern sections of the zone only received around an inch of snow.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong Pacific jet nosing into central Oregon from the northwest drove a cold upper-level low from Canada into the Inland Northwest.  Southwest flow ahead of the trough resulted in a period of moist isentropic ascent across southeastern Washington bringing the first round of light snow.  Snow intensified overnight on the 6th as a surface low deepened over northeastern Oregon setting up a narrow deformation band of moderate to heavy snow.  Many locations across southeastern Washington received between one and three inches of snow but upwards of four to six inches fell within the deformation and across the Washington Palouse.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts ranged from three to five inches leading to hazardous travel during the Friday morning commute.

While warning amounts fell across all cities of the warning zones the highest snowfall amounts in inches are as followed: (13) southwest of Bickleton, (13) northeast of Goldendale, (13) in Naches, (12.3) southeast of Cliffdell, (10) in Lyle, (10) in Snowden, (9.7) in Yakima, (7.5) in Walla Walla, (7) in Dayton, (6) in Ellensburg, and (6) north of Kennewick..

EVENT_NARRATIVE: There were not many reports in this area, but 4 inches of snow in nearby Parkdale, OR and 9 inches in BZ Corner, OR provide an estimate of 4 to 6 inches of snow. There were also early reports of 1 to 2 inches of snow in the Gorge as the event began. There were intermittent closures on Highway 84 due to snow and icy roads.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A frontal system brought snow and ice to Southwest Washington February 7th and 8th after a previous storm produced widespread heavy snow across the area on February 6th.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts ranged between four and seven inches.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold and conditionally unstable air mass had become established across the Inland Northwest as a cold upper-level trough anchored over the region.  A second low pressure system within a 36 hour period tracked across northern Oregon spreading a band of moderate snow within a deformation axis across extreme southeastern Washington and the lower Idaho Panhandle.  As the low pressure system departed to the east, northwest flow in its wake led to numerous snow showers across the rising terrain of the Blue Mountains.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A Weather system brought additional snow and ice to Southwest Washington March 8th. This is the third cold weather event in a series where there was a widespread snow/ice event on March 7th that followed a widespread heavy snow event on the 6th.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The City of Portland issued its first Wireless Emergency Alert in history on March 9th at 8 AM warning people to stay indoors due to dangerous ice conditions. While most of the icing has stopped by then, there was still significant ice loading on branches and power lines as well as several of each downed. Power outages continued into the 9th due to the ice, but ice slowly melted as temperatures crept above freezing. Some ice accumulations reported from spotters include a 0.25 inch in Camas, and a 0.25 inch of ice in Battle Ground.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A Weather system brought additional snow and ice to Southwest Washington February 8th. This is the third cold weather event after a widespread snow/ice event on the 7th, and a  widespread heavy snow event on the 6th.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts across southern Chelan County ranged from five to seven inches.  Further north near Lake Chelan and the Methow Valley, snowfall amounts were between two and three inches.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong Pacific jet with ties to subtropical moisture setup across central Oregon allowing an active storm track along the Washington, Oregon border.  The second low pressure system in as many days took aim on southeastern Washington during the overnight and morning hours of the 8th of February.  A band of light to moderate snow on the northeastern periphery brought one to three inches of snow across the Washington Palouse.  A third low pressure system during the evening of the 8th into the morning of the 9th dropped another three to four inches.  Meanwhile, northeast winds drawn into the system continued to bring modified arctic air from Canada into the region.  The combination of temperatures in the teens and northeast winds between 15 and 25 mph resulted in blowing snow and large drifts across the Palouse closing sections of Highway 27 on each the 8th and 9th of February.  Road closures on the 8th were centered between mile posts 59 and the community of Latah.  On the 9th, Highway 27 was closed between mile posts 48 and 63.

The next wave of precipitation would move in mid day on the 7th and bring widespread snow to the forecast area. While warning amounts fell across all cities of the warning zones the highest snowfall amounts in inches are as followed: (13) southwest of Bickleton, (13) northeast of Goldendale, (13) in Naches, (12.3) southeast of Cliffdell, (10) in Lyle, (10) in Snowden, (9.7) in Yakima, (7.5) in Walla Walla, (7) in Dayton, (6) in Ellensburg, and (6) north of Kennewick..

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The heaviest snow started around 0800 PST with storm total amounts in the three to four inch range across the Spokane Area.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A moist warm front overrunning an established pool of cold air over Eastern Washington resulted in several hours of light to moderate snowfall on the 10th of February.  The heaviest snow accumulations were found in the East Slopes of the Washington Cascades which received between seven to fourteen inches.  The remainder of the region saw snowfall amounts generally under two inches.  The exception was along a narrow corridor across Northeastern Washington, generally south of Pend Oreille River and north of the Palouse, extending east to west from Lincoln County to the Idaho Montana border.  A nearly stationary boundary coupled with the rising terrain resulted in several hours of moderate snow which accumulated between three and four inches over a span of just a few hours.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Light to moderate snow fell across the East Slopes during the morning hours of the 10th ahead of a strong cold front.  Behind the cold front, an unstable air mass and strong westerly flow resulted in numerous convective snow showers along and east of the Cascade Crest.  The morning snow brought between two and four inches then an additional four to eight inches fell at some locations with the post frontal showers.  Locations near the Cascade Crest including Mazama, Holden Village, and Stevens Pass received between nine and thirteen inches of snow from the event.  Further east away from the crest, snowfall amounts were generally in the six to nine inch range.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: One skier, one snowboarder triggered and caught in slide, both partially buried. Skier was able to self-rescue himself and then other rider. Both sustained injuries.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: USFS NWAC station at Mt Baker measured 13 inches snow in 12 hours ending 2 am Feb 12.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A Pacific frontal system brought heavy snow to Mt Baker in the North Cascades. One skier, one snowboarder triggered and caught in slide, both partially buried. Skier was able to self-rescue himself and then other rider. Both sustained injuries.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Light to moderate snow fell across the East Slopes during the evening and overnight hours of the 11th resulting in four to six inches for most locations.  Post frontal convective snow showers slopping across the Cascade Crest brought an additional two to four inches of snow to locations near the Cascade Crest including Mazama, Holden Village, and Stevens Pass.  These locations received between seven and eleven inches of snow throughout the event leading to hazardous travel, especially across the mountain passes.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An atmospheric river overrunning a dome of cold air established over Eastern Washington resulted in an extended period of moderate to heavy precipitation across the region.  Precipitation mainly fell in the form of snow for the East Slopes of the Cascades and northern mountains resulting in snow accumulations of seven to fourteen inches.  In the northern valleys, snow gradually transitioned to rain after two to four inches of snow fell.  A few locations experienced a period of sleet and freezing rain as this transition occurred.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two to four inches of snow fell in the valleys before snow levels climbed near 3000 feet.  In the mountains, seven to fourteen inches of snow was observed.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Three weather stations along the South Washington Coast measured strong winds as a Pacific storm system moved onshore. Cape Disappointment (82SW1 measured a peak gust of 66 mph, Toke Point NOS (TOKW1) measured a gust of 59 mph, and Megler Bridge (ODT76) measured a peak gust of 82 mph.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system resulted in strong winds for the Southwest Washington coast and coast range.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Whidbey Island NUW ASOS recorded 37 gust 58 mph.  Port Townsend had sustained 47 mph wind.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong storm brought marginal high wind to parts of the north interior.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A CWOP in Bellingham recorded wind as high as sustained 45 mph, gusting to 59 mph, for a few hours off and on early in the morning.  Sandy Point Shores recorded sustained 36 mph gusting to 60 mph winds around the same time.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong storm brought marginal high wind to parts of the north interior.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two weather stations reported strong winds in the Southwest Washington Coast Range. The Abernathy RAWS (ABNW1) reported sustained winds of 44 mph with a peak gust of 65 mph, and Naselle Ridge (BPNAS) measures a maximum wind of 92 mph.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system resulted in strong winds for the Southwest Washington coast and coast range.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous areas of northern and central Whitman County experienced flooding between the 12th and 14th.  State route 23 was closed between Sprague and Saint John between mileposts 15 and 43 due to water over the roadway in several locations.    Colfax, WA experienced heavy flooding closing Mill Street from Canyon to Spring which also included mileposts 0 to 1 of SR 272.  Flood waters up to a foot were observed in portions of downtown Colfax.  Water undercut part of the roadway on SR27 five miles south of Oakesdale washing out part of the northbound lane.  Several homes in the community of Ewan were inundated with up to one foot of water.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Numerous areas across the Idaho Panhandle dealt with flooding during the second week of February. While minor flooding is a common occurrence during the late winter months when warmer temperatures, wind, and rain fall on valley snowpack, there was one ingredient of this event that made it unique and rather intense for many locations. This was the intrusion of two Arctic air masses; one in December and one in February. These bitterly cold air masses arrived in the absence of valley snow pack and froze the ground hard and deep. Shortly after the second Arctic air mass, snow began falling across the region with anywhere between six and twelve inches of valley snowfall. Then came an atmospheric river. This drove temperatures and dewpoints above freezing, led to windy conditions, and brought moderate to heavy rainfall. Nearly all the valley snowpack melted in a span of 24 hours.  Due to the rock hard ground, rain and snow melt could not percolate into the frozen ground equating to nearly 100 percent runoff.  This led to big problems in hilly terrain, low spots, and areas susceptible to poor drainage.  Some school districts were forced to delay school because buses were unable to navigate muddy or flooded back roads.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous areas across Lincoln County dealt with flooding between the 12th and 14th.  Some sections of highways that were flooded include SR 23 between mileposts 57 and 60 south of Harrington, SR 231 between mileposts 36 and 42 near Reardon, SR 231 between mileposts 18 and 19 near Edwall, SR 25 between Davenport and Lake Roosevelt, and SR 21 between mileposts 57 and 60 near Harrington.  A creek that runs through the middle of the Edwall flooded the Post Office and adjacent businesses with one to two feet of water.  Edwall-Reardon school district was forced to delay school openings because buses were struggling to navigate muddy dirt roads.  A tech company located on SR 231 reported 30 inches of water flooded its manufacturing facility.  Fortunately, the staff was able to get all valuable equipment off the floor before the flood waters entered.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous areas across Spokane County experienced flooding on the 12th of February.  Due to frozen grounds, the flood problems persisted through the 14th in some cases.  A small ice jam on Coulee Heights Creek caused the creek to become diverted and flow into a private residence.  Water was approximately five feet deep in the garage and surrounding home.  A NWS employee observed up to two inches of water with some mud and small  debris flowing down Rambo Road just north of the Forecast Office.  Water was over a foot deep along the shoulders.  The swift water washed out portions of the shoulder and foundation to the edges of the pavement.  A few blocks away from the Forecast Office, water flooded the West Prairie Village Mobile home park located on the corner of Craig and Haid Lane.  It was estimated that one to two feet of water filled sections of the park.  In southern sections of the county, many secondary roads were flooded in low crossings.  State route 27 just north of Latah near milepost 58 was impassible for a period of time due to water over the road.  Water was also over the roadway along SR 2 two miles west of Airway Heights.  Damage extended into the Spokane Valley with damage or flooding observed near the intersection of Sanson and MacDonald, Crown Street at Forker Draw, Ridgemont Estates on Shamrock Street, and Thorpe Road at Chester Creek.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Icy road conditions in the Ephrata area led to school closures on the 13th of February.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Conditions on the 12th of February were generally mild for February standards with periods of light rain and temperatures in the forties.  By the evening and overnight hours, skies cleared and temperatures cooled into the thirties.  In addition, Arctic air mass intrusions during the last two months had led to a deep hard freeze of the subsurface. These conditions were thought to be responsible for patches of ice along sections of US 195, US 2, and Spokane Area during the morning commute of February 13th.  Numerous accidents, some containing injuries were reported across the area.  Between 1100 PST and 1400 PST, strong winds sustained between 20 and 30 miles per hour along with gusts estimated around 45 miles per hour impacted the Spokane Area snapping a thirty five foot section of a pine tree.  The tree limb fell into a Bengal tiger enclosure at Cat Tales Zoo in Mead, WA.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Icy roadways across the Spokane Area led to multiple accident during the morning commute.  The largest accidents occurred along Highway 2 near Spotted Road and State  Route 195 near Mullen Hill Road.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A large tree branch snapped off a tree and landed in a Bengal tiger enclosure at Cat Tales in Mead, WA.  The 35 foot section of pine tree snapped a guide wire and crashed through two fences that hold the big cats.  No tigers or people were injured during the event.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Light to moderate snow fell across the East Slopes during the early morning hours of the 14th resulting in four to six inches for most locations. Post frontal convective snow showers slopping across the Cascade Crest brought an additional one to three inches of snow to locations near the Cascade Crest including Mazama, Holden Village, and Stevens Pass. A COOP in Mazama reported ten inches from the event.  This led to hazardous travel across the mountain passes.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong westerly jet aimed directly at the Pacific Northwest brought several rounds of moderate to heavy snow to the East Slopes of the Washington Cascades. The accompanying moisture fetch could be traced back to the tropics however adequate cool air damming east of the crest allowed precipitation to remain mainly in the form of snow. Snow to liquid ratios indicated it was a very wet snow. Snow accumulations were generally in the six to ten inch range.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Steady light to moderate snow fell across the East Slopes through the evening hours of the 15th then snow transitioned toward convective post frontal showers with the heaviest activity focusing near the Cascade Crest.  Snowfall amounts generally ranged from six to eight inches with the highest amounts near the crest.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong westerly jet aimed directly at the Pacific Northwest brought several rounds of moderate to heavy snow to the East Slopes of the Washington Cascades.  The accompanying moisture fetch had origins to the tropics however adequate cool air damming east of the crest allowed precipitation to remain mainly in the form of snow.  Snow to liquid ratios indicated it was a very wet snow.  Snow accumulations were generally in the seven to ten inch range along the East Slopes of the Cascades and three to five inches across the Wenatchee Area and Waterville Plateau.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow fell above elevations of 2000 feet.  Snowfall amounts ranged from six inches near Leavenworth to sixteen inches in Holden Village.  Plain picked up between twelve and fourteen inches.  Six to ten inches fell in the upper reaches of the Methow Valley.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Periods of moderate to heavy snow continued for the fifth straight day across the East Slopes of the Washington Cascades.  The persistent westerly jet feeding subtropical moisture into the region was temporarily disrupted as a trough dropped out of the Gulf of Alaska and passed through the region.  Instability within the trough coupled with strong westerly flow promoted consistent orographic showers along the crest which extended well into the upper valleys.  This precipitation regime was gradually replaced with stable snowfall as trough tracked inland and the next plume of deep moisture and associated warm front lifted into the region on the 17th.  Over a foot of snow fell along and adjacent to the crest impacting the communities of Plain, Holden Village, and Mazama.  Snowfall amounts near six inches were common away from the crest in locations like Leavenworth.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow fell at elevations of 2000 feet and higher with the exception of Stehekin, WA which is near the Cascade Crest.  Snowfall amounts at Plain, Leavenworth, and Stehekin were generally in the eight to fourteen inch range.  The most impressive twenty-four hour total was received from a COOP at Holden Village which reported seventeen inches.  This was the seventh snow storm to impact the East Slopes of the Washington Cascades since the 8th of February.  A family of six became stranded in a backcountry cabin located in the Sears Creek drainage.  The family had skied into the cabin on the 15th and were unable to ski out because two to three feet of new snow had fallen in the four day period.  Chelan County Search and Rescue successfully rescued the family utilizing a snow cat.

Over a foot of snow fell along and adjacent to the crest impacting the communities of Plain, Holden Village, and Mazama. EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two passengers were killed and two others were injured when a car lost control on icy roads and ran head on into a semi-truck.  One passenger was ejected from the car.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Conditions on the 20th of February were generally mild for February standards with periods of light rain.  By the evening and overnight hours, skies cleared and temperatures cooled just near the freezing mark.  In addition, Arctic air mass intrusions during the last two months had led to a deep hard freeze of the subsurface.  These conditions were thought to be responsible for patches of ice along sections of US 195 across the Washington Palouse during the early morning hours of February 21st.  A car carrying four passengers lost control near mile post 36 crossing into the southbound lane and running head on into a semi-truck.  Two passengers were killed in the accident and two other were injured.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The East Slopes of the Washington Cascades experienced nearly three days of light to moderate snow and occasionally periods of heavy snow from February 22nd through the morning hours of the 25th.  Snowfall totals over the three day period ranged from eight inches across the eastern reaches of Chelan County to forty inches along and near the Cascade Crest.  Mazama, located in the western reaches of the Methow Valley received seventeen inches of snow.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A complex weather pattern across the Eastern Pacific led to region-wide light to moderate snow.  A closed upper-level high was positioned over southeastern Alaska.  The high steered modified Arctic air southward into the Inland Northwest.  Meanwhile, a moist westerly jet undercut the Alaskan high bringing a source of moisture into the region.  A combination of a stalled frontal boundary, topography, and isentropic processes resulted in region-wide snow.  The heaviest snow was delivered in two main waves; the first occurred from the evening hours of the 22nd through the evening of the 23rd with a second surge of moderate to heavy snow during the day on the 24th.  The heaviest snow accumulations were concentrated across the East Slopes of the Washington Cascades and Central Panhandle Mountains of Idaho which received between one to three feet of snow.  Nearly all other valley locations received between four to ten inches over the multi-day period.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An Arctic front pushed into eastern Washington during the afternoon hours on February 28th.  The modified Arctic air mass intruding into the region out of Canada set up a strong pressure gradient across the area during the overnight hours into March 1st.  This set up strong northeast winds across the Spokane Area, out over the Upper Columbia Basin and into the Moses Lake Area.

The region was under a cold and dry air mass as the calendar flipped over to March 1st with an Arctic boundary pushing south of eastern Washington.  Drier northerly flow flipped around to a moister and mild southerly flow by March 2nd as a sub-tropical plume of moisture impacted the region.  Precipitation fell as snow over all valley locations before transitioning to a wintry mix and eventually rain from south to north as the cold Arctic air slowly eroded away.  Orographics played a big role as to where the heaviest snowfall occurred, including along the east slopes of the northern Cascades and in the Northeast Mountains.  Good isentropic ascent and colder temperatures also led to heavy snowfall across the Spokane Area.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Bus carrying school children slid of the road and flipped on its side in Springdale.  The accident occurred on Cementery Road near Highway 231.  There were twenty-seven children on board the bus and eight of the children were transported to the hospital with injuries.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The region was under a transitioning weather regime through the first week of March.  March 1st came in dry and very cold under a modified Arctic air mass.  This kept soil temperatures below freezing across much of the northeast portion of Washington.  March 2nd into the 3rd brought heavy snow across these same areas as dry northerly flow was replaced by milder and wetter southerly flow.  This wetter and milder flow regime continued into March 5th, but with snow levels lifting above valleys floors.  A pair of Pacific storm systems bringing through more sub-tropical moisture into the region resulted in moderate to heavy rainfall in the valleys.  The first weather system during the early morning hours on March 5th resulted in a short duration mixed precipitation event for portions of the Northeast Mountains.  This lead to pockets of icy roads early in the morning before temperatures warmed up late in the morning and in the afternoon.  The main impact over this wet period was flooding over the Palouse, upper potions of the Columbia Basin and in the Spokane Area.  Flooding was exasperated by low elevation snow melt and frozen soils.

Flood waters inundated a culvert resulting in damage to portions of Hawk Creek Ranch Road.  Pooling of water was reported in Edwall due to culverts being overwhelmed by flood waters.  Damage costs for the event were estimated.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: An Oregon Department of Transportation weather station on Megler Bridge reported high winds for 17 hours with a maximum sustained winds of 50 mph and a peak gust of 72 mph. Another station at Cape Disappointment measured high winds for around 12 hours with maximum sustained winds of 48 mph and a peak gust of 62 mph.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front brought strong winds to Southwest Washington March 5, 2014 during the evening. The associated deep surface low moved inland into Vancouver Island early the next morning (March 6th) dragging a bent-back occluded front across Southwest Washington, and producing another round of strong winds.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Abernathy RAWS (ABNW1) measured high winds for 2 hours early in the aftrnoon on March 6,2014 with a peak gust of 62 mph.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front brought strong winds to Southwest Washington March 5, 2014 during the evening. The associated deep surface low moved inland into Vancouver Island early the next morning (March 6th) dragging a bent-back occluded front across Southwest Washington, and producing another round of strong winds.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Grays River near Rosburg briefly flooded March 6. The river reached flood stage around 11 am March 6th before cresting at 13.2 feet at 2 pm. The river fell below flood stage around 1 am on March 7th.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A moist front resulted in heavy rain for Southwest Washington March 6th, resulting in brief flooding of the Grays River near Rosburg.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Oregon Department of Transportation's weather station on Megler Bridge measured sustained winds of 48 mph with a peak gust of 63 mph for 6 consecutive hours. Sustained winds of 49 mph were also reported at Cape Disappointment for 3 consecutive hours with a peak gust of 59 mph.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A front combined with a coastal barrier jet produced strong winds for the Southwest Washington Coast on March 8, 2014. The NWS Doppler Radar Velocity product detected 50 to 60 kt winds just offshore the coast between 1500 and 4000 feet above the surface.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain resulted in the Grays River near Rosburg to reach flood stage around 7 pm on March 8. The river crested at 15 feet around 1 am on March 9th and fell below flood stage around 6 pm.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A moist front produced heavy rain in Southwest Washington that resulted in brief flooding of the grays River near Rosburg.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The southbound lane of State Route 31 at milepost 11 was blocked by a combination of mud and large rocks.  Time of the debris flow was estimated.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level low pressure system in the Gulf of Alaska late on March 8th into March 9th directed a slow north to south sagging atmospheric river across the area. The origins of this atmospheric river were from off of the Islands of Hawaii. This resulted in abnormally high moisture content for early to mid-March. This was a very mild weather pattern with precipitation falling as rain even over the highest mountain peaks.  Moderate to heavy rain was reported in the Northeast Mountains, especially for areas closer to the Idaho border.

A vigorous occluded front pushed across the region through the early afternoon hours.  Steepening low to mid-level lapse rates resulted in a destabilizing atmosphere for the afternoon due to warming at the surface from the sun and cooling aloft by the approaching upper level shortwave trough.  Forcing along the upper level wave produced a squall line that stretched across the Palouse up into the Spokane Area.  Damaging winds were produced along the squall line up to the Idaho border.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A forty-foot tree fell on a house from winds behind the squall line.  Damage costs were estimated.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: On a warm and dry 22nd of March, 2014, a large landslide occurred four miles east of the town of Oso, Washington. The slide debris, traveling at over 60 miles per hour, crossed the entire river valley, covering an area of over a square mile with an approximate deposit thickness of 15 to 75 feet in some areas. The force of the slide flow caused 43 fatalities, 12 injuries, destroyed 37 homes, and wiped out SR 530 for over a mile. In addition, the slide debris completely blocked the North Fork Stillaguamish River for over 24 hours, backing up a pool of water that flooded the valley about 2 miles upstream and reached approximately 20 feet deep, inundating an additional 6 homes. The cause of the slide is not fully known, though precipitation in the previous months to years contributed to the ground failure. A rain gage located 2 miles west of the slide had 19.93 inches of rain in the 40 days leading up to the slide. |As of March 19th the nearest reporting station Arlington, had reported 7.14 inches of rain, which is about 2 inches shy of the record 9.23 for the entire month of March.  Three days before the slide, the area received close to an inch of rain in one day. Most all of the fatalities occurred at the permanent homes impacted by the slide.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A relatively dry October 2013 through early February 2014 period with precipitation running around only 50 percent of normal turned unusually wet one week into February and continued through March. Precipitation during February and March ranked in the top 10 all-time for this time period, running between 150 and 200 percent of average. ||On a warm and dry 22nd of March, 2014, a large landslide occurred four miles east of the town of Oso, Washington. The slide debris, traveling at over 60 miles per hour, crossed the entire river valley, covering an area of over a square mile with an approximate deposit thickness of 15 to 75 feet in some areas. The force of the slide flow caused 43 fatalities, 12 injuries, destroyed 37 homes, and wiped out SR 530 for over a mile. In addition, the slide debris completely blocked the North Fork Stillaguamish River for over 24 hours, backing up a pool of water that flooded the valley about 2 miles upstream and reached approximately 20 feet deep, inundating an additional 6 homes. The cause of the slide is not fully known, though precipitation in the previous months to years contributed to the ground failure. A rain gage located 2 miles west of the slide had 19.93 inches of rain in the 40 days leading up to the slide. |As of March 19th the nearest reporting station Arlington, had reported 7.14 inches of rain, which is about 2 inches shy of the record 9.23 for the entire month of March.  Three days before the slide, the area received close to an inch of rain in one day.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The tornado destroyed a carport at one house. The trestles were also cracked inside of the garage. A utility pole was bent back (leaning) which was being supported by a digger. The garbage can was found in the trees; the trees were damaged. Several shingles were ripped from roofs.  A road sign and several more trees were also damaged nearby.  At the local Eagle's Club, siding was peeled back on one corner with branches strewn across the property.  Estimated peak wind speeds of 75 mph.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A gust front with winds estimated between 30 and 45 mph tore off a secondary metal rood from a one story apartment building located near the intersection of W Manilla and E Espanola Rd.  A section of roof blew into the powerlines resulting in power outages along the street.  No damage was observed to adjacent structures or vegetation.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms near the Spokane Stevens County border collapsed on the afternoon off the May 5th sending gusty north outflow winds of 30 to 45 mph through Medical Lake, WA.  The winds resulted in localized roof damage to a small apartment building.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Large rocks in roadway blocked SR20 Eastbound lane only near milepost 318 in Ferry county. Report received via e-mail from Washington State Patrol.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Landslide allowed large rocks to obstruct SR20 eastbound at milepost 318 in Ferry county or 16 miles east of republic.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two skiers in party, one caught by a natural avalanche while ascending on foot and carried several thousand feet, one fatality.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On Mt. Shuskan, a skier was caught by a natural avalanche while ascending on foot and carried several thousand feet, one fatality.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Public reported golf ball size hail.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered thunderstorms developed across Northeastern Washington during the afternoon of June 3rd in an environment characterized by weak shear and moderate instability.  A weak midlevel dropping south out of British Columbia enhanced lift during the afternoon hours.  Two storms briefly became very strong to severe producing hail in excess of one inch.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A grass fire sometime after 2300 PDT Sunday evening burned a motor home and farm tractor on Wilmorth Road off Highway 97 east of Chelan, WA.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Several weeks of warm and dry weather coupled with ongoing drought conditions from the previous winter resulted in very dry fuels around the Wenatchee Area.  Gusty winds on the evening of the 8th helped fan a grass fire some time after 2300 PDT near Chelan, WA.  The fire was small and contained after a few hours but managed to burn a motor home and farm tractor.  The cause of the fire is unknown.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several businesses along Howard Street near the intersection of 2nd Avenue were flooded when heavy rain overwhelmed the city's storm drains.  Water was spilling back into buildings through toilets and drain pipes.  Among the businesses were The Interplayers Theatre and Howard Street Boxing.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A moist and unstable atmosphere over Eastern Washington coupled with weak shear led to widely scattered thunderstorms on the afternoon of June 26th.  A cluster of storms moved through downtown Spokane depositing upwards of an inch of rainfall in less than an hour.  The city's storm drains were overwhelmed and several businesses near the intersection of 2nd and Howard Street were flooded.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: An injury from swimming in the Toutle River, WA during a hot weather spell could be indirectly related to the hot temperatures on July 1, 2014.  A man and two children were swimming in the Toutle River when a strong current took the three of them under water. The girl's mother jumped in to help, and also got caught in the current. The man was able to get the woman, her two daughters, and himself to shore and was later airlifted to the hospital for injuries received during the process.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level ridge combined with a surface thermal trough and low level offshore winds resulted in a hot day across Southwest Washington where inland temperatures peaked in the upper 90s inland and the upper 80s along the coast. The NWS Portland office had a heat advisory in effect. Many people flocked to the rivers to cool from the heat and there were unfortunately a drowning. Another man was hospitalized after rescuing a woman and two children from the Toutle River.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A drowning in the Lewis River near Yacolt, WA is indirectly related to the hot temperatures as the victim likely went to the river to gain relief from the heat . The victim was a 44 year old man that drowned after jumping from the rocks at Moulton Falls.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level ridge combined with a surface thermal trough and low level offshore winds resulted in a hot day across Southwest Washington where inland temperatures peaked in the upper 90s inland and the upper 80s along the coast. The NWS Portland office had a heat advisory in effect. Many people flocked to the rivers to cool from the heat and there were unfortunately a drowning. Another man was hospitalized after rescuing a woman and two children from the Toutle River.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two siblings playing in the shore near Boldtad Beach was caught in a rip that dragged them out to sea. The older sibling, a 11 year old girl pushed her younger brother towards the shore before she drifted further out to sea and drowned. The younger boy was rescued after being in the water for 30 minutes. He was found with only his face above the water, and was hospitalized for injuries.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Two siblings playing in the shore near Boldtad Beach was caught in a rip that dragged them out to sea. The older sibling drowned, and the younger survived, but was hospitalized.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The lightning-caused fire, which began July 14, blackened 269,186 acres; leveled approximately 325 homes; 146 barns, outbuildings and fences; damaged utilities; killed cattle, wildlife and other stock; and destroyed or damaged orchards, crops, forest and range land. Total cost to fight the fire was approximately 87 million dollars.  The fire spanned two different public zones and cost and acreage is highly uncertain per zone.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The largest fire in Washington State history is now the 2014 Carlton Complex.  Central Washington was in drought status.  The fire was started by lightning on July 14.  The complex started as four fires; the Stokes Fire, The Gold Hikes Fire, the French Creek Fire, and the Cougar Flat Fire.  Explosive fire activity occurred on July 16th with very hot, dry, and unstable conditions in place.  Each fire then made runs over the ridgetops and grew into one fire between July 17th and July 18th as hot and windy conditions developed.  The fire rapidly spread through the communities of Methow, Pateros, Carlton, and Olema, and portions of Brewster consuming approximately 325 homes, barns, outbuildings and fences, utilities, cattle and livestock, and orchards, crops, forest, and range land in its path.  The fire burned 269,186 acres consisting of a combination of brush, timber and heavy fuels.
